South Korean President Roh Moo-Hyun called for an investigation into illegal recordings involving Ambassador Hong Seok-Hyun and Samsung executives in 1997.
The scandal revealed potential corruption and illicit donations to politicians during the 2002 presidential poll.
Ambassador Hong offered to resign amid suspicions of facilitating slush funds to candidates.
The National Intelligence Service admitted to wiretapping influential figures until 2002, causing public outrage.
Former President Kim Dae-jung's reputation was also marred by allegations of secret payments and illegal wiretapping during his administration.
The scandal highlighted societal concerns about government-business collusion and civil liberties.
